{
  "texts": [
    "Explanations can be delivered in two ways: post-hoc (model agnostic) and directly from an explainable model (model intrinsic) (Kenny et al., 2021).",
    "Model inherent explanations, also known as interpretable models, that use various methods can explain prediction and the decisionmaking processes.",
    "This implies that the model is inherently transparent and interpretable.",
    "Post-hoc explanations, which are model agnostic in nature, lack inherent explainability.",
    "Hence, the model continues to function as an opaque entity even though post-decision explanations are generated."
  ]
}